# Forward and Futures Prices  

# Aims  

• To construct a synthetic or [replication portfolio](../Part%20V%20-%20Options%20Pricing/Chapter%2022%20-%20BOPM:%20Implementation.md) whose cash fows mimic the cash fows in an actual [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md).   
• To show how [cash-and-carry arbitrage](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2015/Dollar%20Rolls.md) can be used to determine the correct (no-[arbitrage](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%207/Arbitrage%20Pricing%20of%20Derivatives.md)) ‘fair’ price for a [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) on a (non-dividend paying) stock.   
• To interpret [cash-and-carry arbitrage](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2015/Dollar%20Rolls.md) in terms of the [implied repo rate](../../Fixed%20Income%20Derivatives/The%20Futures%20Bond%20Basis:%20government%20bond%20futures%20and%20basis%20%20trading.md) and the actual repo rate.   
• To extend our [arbitrage](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%207/Arbitrage%20Pricing%20of%20Derivatives.md) approach to determine the [fair forward price](.md) when the [underlying asset](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Risk%20Neutral%20Pricing%20of%20Options.md) pays an income stream (e.g. dividends on a stock) or has [storage costs](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Primary%20vs.%20Secondary%20Commodities.md) (e.g. oil, wheat) or can be used as an input to the production process (e.g. the convenience yield of owning oil).   
• To distinguish between the price of a [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) at inception and the value of a [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) that has been in existence for some time.  

# 3.1 PRICING FORWARD CONTRACTS  

In this section we analyse how forward and future prices are determined as functions of known variables such as the current market price of the [underlying asset](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Risk%20Neutral%20Pricing%20of%20Options.md) and the [risk-free interest rate](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Asset%20Pricing%20Theory%20Overview/Chapter%2012%20-%20Derivatives/Exercises.md). Forward contracts are easier to analyse than [futures contracts](../../Mathematics%20of%20the%20Financial%20Markets.md), since the latter have the added complication of [daily settlement](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Pricing%20and%20Hedging%20Implications%20of%20Daily%20Sett.md) (i.e. marking-to-market) whereas for the [forward contract](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Points%20in%20Currency.md) there is one payment at the maturity date. However, it can be shown that the [futures price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Futures%20Price%20and%20the%20Quality%20Option%20Before%20E.md) closely follows that of the [forward price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Forward%20Contracts%20and%20Forward%20Prices.md) (for contracts with the same maturity date). Therefore, for the most part the reader can consider the analysis of ‘forward’ and ‘[futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md)’ prices as being interchangeable. In general we assume:  

zero transactions costs   
• zero tax rates   
• agents can borrow or lend unlimited amounts at the [risk-free rate](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Black%20Scholes%20Derivation.md) of interest   
• short-selling of the [underlying asset](../../../Financial%20Instruments/Financial%20Derivatives%20and%20Quantitative%20Methods/Risk%20Neutral%20Pricing%20of%20Options.md) is possible   
• risk-free [arbitrage opportunities](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%208-%20Markets,%20Meltdowns,%20and%20Arbitrage/Class%20Note%2013%20The%20LTCM%20Meltdown.md) are instantaneously eliminated.  

For the most part we use (risk-free) [arbitrage](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%207/Arbitrage%20Pricing%20of%20Derivatives.md) to price [futures contracts](../../Mathematics%20of%20the%20Financial%20Markets.md) and this method is also referred to as the cost of carry method.  

# 3.1.1 Non-income Paying Security  

Consider the [futures price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Futures%20Price%20and%20the%20Quality%20Option%20Before%20E.md) on a stock (which pays no dividends). The [futures](../../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%203%20-%20Futures%20Markets/Futures%20Not%20Subject%20to%20Cash-And-Carry.md) contract is for the delivery of a single stock in 3 months’ time (Figure 3.1). We set up a situation where initially it is possible to make a risk-free [arbitrage](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%207/Arbitrage%20Pricing%20of%20Derivatives.md) proft because the quoted [futures price](../../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2011/Futures%20Price%20and%20the%20Quality%20Option%20Before%20E.md) is incorrect. Consider the following ‘prices’:  
